  "prompt": "Do you use Java or JavaScript to make an Android game?",
  "response": "To make an Android game, you primarily use **Java** or **Kotlin**. These are the **official programming languages** supported by Android development using the **Android SDK** (Software Development Kit). \n\n- **Java** has traditionally been the most widely used language for Android development. Many older apps and games were built using Java.\n- **Kotlin** is now the **preferred language** for Android development, designed to be more concise and modern than Java. It is fully interoperable with Java, meaning you can use both in the same project.\n\n### Choosing JavaScript for Android Games\nIf you want to use **JavaScript**, you would typically use a **game engine** or framework like:\n- **React Native** (for simpler games/apps)\n- **Unity** (with C# for more complex games, but it also supports JavaScript-like scripting via **UnityScript**, which is now deprecated)\n- **Phaser** (a JavaScript game framework, but often used for web-based games)\n- **Cocos2d-x** (supports JavaScript for cross-platform game development)\n\nHowever, using JavaScript for Android games is less common and not the native approach. It\u2019s better suited for web-based or cross-platform games rather than native Android development.\n\n### Best Option for Android Games\nIf you\u2019re building a native Android game, **Kotlin** is the best choice. If you\u2019re building a cross-platform game or using a game engine, consider **Unity** (C#) or **Unreal Engine** (C++). JavaScript is better suited for web-based or hybrid game development.",
